<section xml:id="section-72">
	<title>Trigonometric Integrals</title>
	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					Apply strategies for evaluating integrals of the forms for integers <m>m,n\geq 0</m>, potentially using trigonometric identities: 
					<ul>
						<li>
							<m>\ds \int \sin^mx\cos^nx\, dx</m> 
						</li>
						<li>
							<m>\ds \int \sec^mx\tan^nx\, dx</m>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<subsection xml:id="section-72-beforeclass">
		<title>Before Class</title>
		<figure>
			<caption>Pre-Class Video 1</caption>
				<url href = "https://mymedia.ou.edu/media/7.2-1/1_asqv45iu"/>
		</figure>

		<subsubsection xml:id="section-72-trig-identities">
			<title>Trigonometric Identities</title>

			<p>
				Here are some identities from trigonometry which will be helpful as we move through this section:
			</p>
			<p>
				<tabular top="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin^2\theta + \cos^2\theta = 1</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin 2\theta = 2\sin\theta\cos\theta</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\cos 2\theta = 1-2\sin^2\theta</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\cos 2\theta = 2\cos^2\theta - 1</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\tan^2\theta + 1 = \sec^2\theta</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>1+\cot^2\theta = \csc^2\theta</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin (\theta + \phi) = \sin\theta\cos\phi + \sin\phi\cos\theta</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin(\theta - \phi) =\sin\theta\cos\phi -\sin\phi\cos\theta</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\cos (\theta + \phi) = \cos\theta\cos\phi - \sin\theta\sin\phi</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\cos(\theta - \phi) = \cos\theta\cos\phi + \sin\theta\sin\phi</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>

			<p>
				Occasionally, you'll want to rearrange some of these identities to arrive at new ones:	
			</p>
			<p>
				<tabular top="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin\theta\cos\phi = \dfrac{1}{2}[\sin(\theta - \phi) + \sin (\theta + \phi)]</m>
						</cell>
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\sin\theta\sin\phi = \dfrac{1}{2}[\cos(\theta - \phi) - \cos(\theta + \phi)]</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row bottom="medium">
						<cell halign="center">
							<m>\cos\theta\cos\phi =\dfrac{1}{2}[\cos(\theta-\phi) + \cos (\theta + \phi)]</m>
						</cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>
		</subsubsection>

		<subsubsection xml:id="section-72-trig-integrals">
			<title>Trigonometric Integrals</title>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute <m>\ds \int \sin^3 x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \sin^3 x\, dx = -\cos x + \dfrac{1}{3}\cos^3x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute <m>\ds \int \sin^5x\cos^2x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \sin^5x\cos^2x\, dx = -\dfrac{1}{7}\cos^7x + \dfrac{2}{5}\cos^5x-\dfrac{1}{3}\cos^3x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the area under the curve of <m>f(x) = \sin^2x</m> from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int_0^{\pi} \sin^2x\, dx = \dfrac{\pi}{2}</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute <m>\ds \int \cos^4x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \cos^4x\, dx = \dfrac{3}{8}x + \dfrac{1}{5}\sin 2x + \dfrac{1}{32}\sin 4x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
		</subsubsection>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="section-72-preclass">
		<title>Pre-Class Activities</title>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use this space to write any questions you might have from the videos.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Answers vary
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int \sin^2 x\cos^3x\, dx</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int \sin^2 x\cos^3x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{3}\sin^3x - \dfrac{1}{5}\sin^5x + C</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int \sin x\cos x\, dx</m> in four ways: (1) using the substitution <m>u = \cos x</m>; (2) using the substitution <m>u = \sin x</m>; (3) using the double-angle identity for sine; (4) using integration by parts.  Compare your work between the four methods.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ol marker="1">
						<li>
							Using the cosine substitution, we get <m>-\dfrac{1}{2}\cos^2x+C</m>
						</li>
						<li>
							Using the sine substitution, we get <m>\dfrac{1}{2}\sin^2x + C</m>
						</li>
						<li>
							Using the double-angle identity, we get <m>-\dfrac{1}{4}\cos 2x + C</m>
						</li>
						<li>
							If we set <m>u=\sin x</m> and <m>dv = \cos x\, dx</m>, we get 
							<me>
								\ds \int \sin x\cos x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{2}\sin^2x + C 
							</me>
							However, if we set <m>u=\cos x</m> and <m>dv = \sin x\, dx</m>, we get
							<me>
								\ds \int \sin x\cos x\, dx = -\dfrac{1}{2}\cos^2x + C
							</me>
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
				<p>
					It seems as though we should get the same answer for all four integrals, but we don't. However, each of these answers can be transformed into the other by using the trigonometric identities listed in the identity table earlier.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="section-72-inclass">
		<title>In Class</title>
		<subsubsection xml:id="section-72-strategies">
			<title>Strategies for Trig Integrals</title>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Evaluating <m>\ds \int \sin^mx\cos^nx\, dx</m></title>
				<p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							If the power of cosine is odd: 
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\ds \int \sin^mx\cos^{2k+1}x\, dx \amp = \int\sin^m x\cos^{2k}x\cdot \cos x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int \sin^m x (\cos^2x)^k\cos x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int \sin^m x (1-\sin^2x)^k\cos x\, dx
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Now set <m>u = \sin x</m>, simplify, and integrate.
						</li>
						<li>
							If the power of sine is odd:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\ds \int \sin^{2k+1}x\cos^n x\, dx \amp = \int (\sin^2 x)^k\cdot \sin x\cdot \cos^n x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int (1-\cos^2x)^k\cdot \cos^n x\cdot \sin x\, dx
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Now set <m>u = \cos x</m>, simplify, and integrate.
						</li>
						<li>
							If the powers of sine and cosine are even: use the power reducing identities <m>\sin^2x = \dfrac{1}{2}(1-\cos 2x)</m> or <m>\cos^2x = \dfrac{1}{2}(1+\cos 2x)</m>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \sin^3\theta\cos^4\theta \, d\theta</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>
							\ds \int \sin^3\theta\cos^4\theta \, d\theta = \dfrac{1}{7}\cos^7x - \dfrac{1}{5}\cos^5x + C
						</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \tan x \sec x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \tan x \sec x\, dx = \sec x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Evaluating <m>\ds \int \tan^mx\sec^nx\, dx</m></title>
				<p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							If the power of secant is even:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\ds \int \tan^mx\sec^{2k}x\, dx \amp = \int \tan^m x\sec^{2k-2}\cdot \sec^2x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int \tan^m x (\sec^2x)^{k-1}\cdot \sec^2 x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int \tan^m x (1+\tan^2x)^{k-1}\cdot \sec^2 x\, dx
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Now set <m>u = \tan x</m>, simplify, and integrate.
						</li>
						<li>
							If the power of tangent is odd:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\ds \int \tan^{2k+1}x \sec^n x\, dx \amp = \int \tan^{2k} x\cdot \tan x \cdot \sec^{n-1} x\cdot \sec x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int (\tan^2x)^k\cdot\sec^{n-1}x\cdot \sec x\tan x\, dx
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp = \ds \int (\sec^2x-1)^k\cdot \sec^{n-1}x\cdot \sec x\tan x\, dx
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Now let <m>u = \sec x</m>, simplify, and integrate.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \tan^3\theta\sec^5\theta\, d\theta</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \tan^3\theta\sec^5\theta\, d\theta = \dfrac{1}{7}\sec^7 x - \dfrac{1}{5}\sec^5 x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Show that <m>\ds \int \sec x\, dx = \ln |\sec x + \tan x| + C</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Multiply the integrand by a form of one: 
						<me>
							\sec x = \sec x\cdot \dfrac{\sec x + \tan x}{\sec x + \tan x}
						</me>
						So that we have
						<me>
							\ds \int \sec x\, dx = \int \dfrac{\sec^2x + \sec x\tan x}{\sec x + \tan x}\, dx
						</me>
						Let <m>u = \sec x + \tan x</m>. So, <m>du = (\sec x\tan x + \sec^2x)\, dx</m>. Rewriting gives
						<me>
							\ds \int \dfrac{\sec^2x + \sec x\tan x}{\sec x + \tan x}\, dx = \int \dfrac{1}{u}\, du = \ln |u| + C
						</me>
						Replacing gives
						<me>
							\ln |\sec x + \tan x| + C
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \tan^3x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \tan^3x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{2}\sec^2 x + \ln |\cos x| + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find <m>\ds \int \sec^3x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \sec^3x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{2}(\sec x\tan x + \ln |\sec x + \tan x|) + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
			
			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \sin 3x\cos 4x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \sin 3x\cos 4x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{2}\cos x - \dfrac{1}{14}\cos 7x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int \cos 5x\cos 7x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int \cos 5x\cos 7x\, dx = \dfrac{1}{4}\sin 2x + \dfrac{1}{24}\sin 12x + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \csc^4\theta\cot^4\theta\, d\theta</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \csc^4\theta\cot^4\theta\, d\theta = \dfrac{12}{35}</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find <m>\ds \int_0^{\pi/2} \sin^2x\cos^2x\, dx</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int_0^{\pi/2} \sin^2x\cos^2x\, dx = \dfrac{\pi}{16}</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Evaluate <m>\ds \int t\sin^2 t\, dt</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\ds \int t\sin^2 t\, dt = \dfrac{1}{4}t^2-\dfrac{1}{4}t\sin 2t - \dfrac{1}{8}\cos 2t + C</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
		</subsubsection>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="section-72-afterclass">
		<title>After Class Activities</title>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Explain why <m>\ds \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} \sin mx \cos nx = 0</m> for any positive integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>.  There are several ways of coming to this answer!
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Answers vary
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int_0^\pi \cos^4(2t)\, dt</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int_0^\pi \cos^4(2t)\, dt = \dfrac{3\pi}{8}</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int \sqrt{\cos\theta}\sin^3\theta \, d\theta</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int \sqrt{\cos\theta}\sin^3\theta \, d\theta = \dfrac{2}{7}\cos^{7/2}\theta - \dfrac{2}{3}\cos^{3/2}\theta + C</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find <m>\ds \int \tan^2\theta \sec^4\theta\, d\theta</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int \tan^2\theta \sec^4\theta\, d\theta = \dfrac{1}{3}\tan^3 \theta + \dfrac{1}{5}\tan^5\theta + C</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int_0^{\pi/2} \cos 5t\cos 10t\, dt</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int_0^{\pi/2} \cos 5t\cos 10t\, dt = \dfrac{1}{10}\sin 5t + \dfrac{1}{30}\sin 15t + C</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\ds \int \dfrac{dx}{\cos x - 1}</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\ds \int \dfrac{dx}{\cos x - 1} = \csc x + \cot x + C</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
	</subsection>
</section>